The paper deals with the complexity of reconfiguration problems on graphs, which is a topic in discrete mathematics (cs.DM). The specific problems studied involve independent sets and colorability, which are both topics in computational complexity (cs.CC). The paper also uses techniques from graph theory (cs.DS) and specifically focuses on split graphs (cs.CG), which are a well-studied class of graphs with interesting properties. Finally, the paper involves some game theory and strategic decision-making (cs.GT) in the context of the token sliding rule. Overall, the paper seems to fit well into these five categories.
